# Step 8: Docker Image Retention & Cleanup

**Phase:** 8 -- Build Caching, Log Streaming & Rollback
**Step:** 8 of 8
**Status:** Not Started
**Depends on:** Phase 5 (Docker client), Step 5 (Rollback -- images must not be pruned if they are rollback targets)

---

## Goal

Implement `pruneImages()` in `packages/core/src/providers/docker/client.ts` to keep only the last 10 Docker images per project (configurable via `BUILD_LIMITS.MAX_IMAGES_PER_PROJECT`). Pruning runs after each successful production deploy. Preview deployment images are deleted when the PR is closed. This prevents the VPS's 80 GB disk from filling up with stale images.

---

## Background

Every build produces a Docker image tagged `{project}:{commit-sha}`. Over time, these images accumulate. A typical Next.js app image is 150-300 MB. With 10+ deploys per week across multiple projects, disk usage grows by 1-3 GB per week without cleanup.

From `__spec.md__` Section 5:

> Keep last 10 Docker images per project. Older images are pruned automatically.

From `__spec.md__` Section 6 (Preview Deployments):

> Preview images deleted after PR is closed (not counted toward the 10-image retention limit).

### Constants

From `packages/shared/src/constants/deployment.ts`:

```typescript
BUILD_LIMITS.MAX_IMAGES_PER_PROJECT = 10  // configurable retention count
```

---

## Implementation

### File: `packages/core/src/providers/docker/client.ts`

Replace the `pruneImages` TODO stub:

```typescript
import Dockerode from "dockerode";
import { createLogger } from "@gblockparty/shared/backend";

const logger = createLogger("docker-client");

/**
 * Remove old Docker images for a project, keeping only the most recent `keepCount`.
 * Images currently in use by running containers are never removed.
 */
export async function pruneImages(
  docker: Dockerode,
  projectName: string,
  keepCount: number,
): Promise<{ removed: string[]; kept: string[] }> {
  // 1. List all images for this project
  const allImages = await docker.listImages({
    filters: {
      reference: [`${projectName}:*`],
    },
  });

  if (allImages.length <= keepCount) {
    logger.info(
      { projectName, imageCount: allImages.length, keepCount },
      "No images to prune",
    );
    return { removed: [], kept: allImages.map((i) => i.RepoTags?.[0] ?? i.Id) };
  }

  // 2. Sort by creation date (newest first)
  const sorted = allImages.sort((a, b) => b.Created - a.Created);

  // 3. Identify images to keep (newest N)
  const toKeep = sorted.slice(0, keepCount);
  const toPrune = sorted.slice(keepCount);

  // 4. Get running container image IDs to avoid removing in-use images
  const containers = await docker.listContainers({ all: false }); // only running
  const inUseImageIds = new Set(containers.map((c) => c.ImageID));

  // 5. Remove old images
  const removed: string[] = [];
  const kept: string[] = toKeep.map((i) => i.RepoTags?.[0] ?? i.Id);

  for (const imageInfo of toPrune) {
    const imageId = imageInfo.Id;
    const imageTag = imageInfo.RepoTags?.[0] ?? imageId;

    // Skip if the image is in use by a running container
    if (inUseImageIds.has(imageId)) {
      logger.info({ imageTag }, "Skipping in-use image");
      kept.push(imageTag);
      continue;
    }

    try {
      const image = docker.getImage(imageId);
      await image.remove({ force: false });
      removed.push(imageTag);
      logger.info({ imageTag }, "Image removed");
    } catch (error) {
      // Image might be referenced by other tags or intermediate layers
      logger.warn({ imageTag, error }, "Failed to remove image");
      kept.push(imageTag);
    }
  }

  logger.info(
    { projectName, removed: removed.length, kept: kept.length },
    "Image pruning complete",
  );

  return { removed, kept };
}
```

### Preview Image Cleanup

Preview images follow a different naming convention: `{project}:pr-{N}-{sha}`.

When a PR is closed (webhook event `pull_request.closed`), all images for that PR should be deleted:

```typescript
/**
 * Remove all Docker images for a specific preview deployment (PR).
 * Called when a PR is closed or merged.
 */
export async function removePreviewImages(
  docker: Dockerode,
  projectName: string,
  prNumber: number,
): Promise<string[]> {
  const pattern = `${projectName}:pr-${prNumber}-*`;

  const images = await docker.listImages({
    filters: {
      reference: [pattern],
    },
  });

  // Also check for running containers using these images
  const containers = await docker.listContainers({ all: false });
  const inUseImageIds = new Set(containers.map((c) => c.ImageID));

  const removed: string[] = [];

  for (const imageInfo of images) {
    const imageId = imageInfo.Id;
    const imageTag = imageInfo.RepoTags?.[0] ?? imageId;

    if (inUseImageIds.has(imageId)) {
      logger.warn({ imageTag }, "Skipping in-use preview image");
      continue;
    }

    try {
      const image = docker.getImage(imageId);
      await image.remove({ force: false });
      removed.push(imageTag);
      logger.info({ imageTag }, "Preview image removed");
    } catch (error) {
      logger.warn({ imageTag, error }, "Failed to remove preview image");
    }
  }

  return removed;
}
```

---

## Integration Points

### 1. After Successful Production Deploy

In `packages/core/src/deploy/deployer.ts`, call `pruneImages()` after a successful production deployment:

```typescript
// At the end of Deployer.deploy(), after status is set to "ready"
import { pruneImages } from "../providers/docker/client";
import { BUILD_LIMITS } from "@gblockparty/shared/constants";

// ... deploy success ...

// Prune old images (fire-and-forget, non-blocking)
pruneImages(docker, project.slug, BUILD_LIMITS.MAX_IMAGES_PER_PROJECT).catch((error) => {
  logger.warn({ error, projectName: project.slug }, "Image pruning failed");
});
```

Pruning is fire-and-forget -- it runs after the deployment is complete and serving traffic. A pruning failure does not affect the deployment.

### 2. After PR Close (Preview Cleanup)

In the GitHub webhook handler for `pull_request.closed` events:

```typescript
// In the PR close handler
import { removePreviewImages } from "@gblockparty/core/providers/docker/client";

// After stopping the preview container and removing Caddy route:
await removePreviewImages(docker, project.slug, prNumber);
```

### 3. After Rollback

After a successful rollback (in `rollbackDeployment()`), pruning is not needed because rollback reuses an existing image and does not create a new one. The next production deploy will trigger pruning.

---

## Image Tagging Convention

Understanding the image tag format is important for pruning:

| Type | Tag Format | Example | Counted in Retention |
|------|-----------|---------|---------------------|
| Production | `{slug}:{commit-sha}` | `myapp:a1b2c3d4` | Yes |
| Preview | `{slug}:pr-{N}-{commit-sha}` | `myapp:pr-42-e5f6g7h8` | No (separate cleanup) |
| Rollback | No new image (reuses existing) | N/A | N/A |

The `pruneImages()` function uses `{projectName}:*` as the reference filter. This matches both production and preview tags. However, preview images should be cleaned up separately when the PR closes, not counted against the retention limit.

To avoid pruning preview images during production pruning, filter them out:

```typescript
// In pruneImages(), after listing images:
const productionImages = allImages.filter((img) => {
  const tag = img.RepoTags?.[0] ?? "";
  // Exclude preview images (pr-N-sha pattern)
  return !tag.includes(":pr-");
});
```

---

## Edge Cases

1. **Fewer than 10 images**: `pruneImages()` returns early, nothing to remove.
2. **Image in use by a running container**: Skipped. Docker prevents removal of in-use images, but we check proactively to avoid error logs.
3. **Image referenced by multiple tags**: `docker.getImage(id).remove()` removes the image by ID. If the image has multiple tags, only the specific tag reference is removed. The image data is removed when all tag references are gone.
4. **Concurrent deploys creating images**: Pruning runs after deploy completion. If another deploy is in progress, its image will not appear in the list yet (not built yet). No race condition.
5. **Pruning removes a potential rollback target**: Rollback targets older than position 10 in the image list will be pruned. The rollback mechanism (Step 5) checks for image existence and returns a clear error. The dashboard UI could gray out rollback buttons for pruned images.
6. **Dangling images (no tag)**: `docker.listImages({ filters: { reference: [...] } })` only matches tagged images. Dangling images from failed builds are not cleaned up by this function. A separate `docker image prune` can be run periodically if needed.
7. **PR with multiple pushes**: Each push to a PR creates a new preview image. When the PR closes, `removePreviewImages()` removes all images matching `pr-{N}-*` for that PR.

---

## Disk Space Estimation

| Metric | Value |
|--------|-------|
| Typical Next.js image size | 150-300 MB |
| Images retained per project | 10 |
| Max disk per project (production) | 3 GB |
| Projects on VPS | ~5-10 |
| Max production image disk usage | 15-30 GB |
| VPS disk capacity | 80 GB |
| Available for other uses | 50-65 GB |

With 10 images retained per project and ~10 projects, image storage uses 15-30 GB of the 80 GB disk. This leaves ample room for the OS, Docker layers, build caches, and application data.

